<HEADLINE>
FT  02 DEC 92 / UK Company News: Thames TV forecasts turnover in excess of
Pounds 100m next year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THAMES Television, which ceases to be an ITV broadcaster at the end of this
month, expects a turnover of more than Pounds 100m next year.
Mr Richard Dunn, chief executive of the largest ITV company, outbid by
Carlton Television, made the forecast last night at the Royal Television
Society.
'We have moved within 12 months from team-player public service broadcaster
to sole television trader, whose job it is to please viewers through any
channels of any medium in any country,' Mr Dunn said.
Thames expects its television production business next year to bring in
between Pounds 45m and Pounds 55m. Its international distribution arm should
have a turnover of Pounds 15m while Reeces, its US production arm, should
have revenue of Pounds 30m. Thames' studios at Teddington should bring in
Pounds 5m.
UK Gold, founded by Thames and the BBC would, Mr Dunn forecast, be worth as
much as all but the largest ITV companies by the end of the decade.
Mr Dunn admitted last night that he did not have high expectations in 'the
indiscriminate, unnecessary and destructive' auction for ITV franchises. 'We
bid the maximum the London weekday licence was worth to us, close to Pounds
33m per annum. I would not have bid any more,' he said.
Mr Dunn detailed how there were several series of talks for the sale of
Thames to Carlton but that each time discussions collapsed on price.
Mr Dunn said if Carlton had acquired control of Thames it would have had no
qualified rival in the auction and 'could have saved itself Pounds 43m per
year for 10 years'.
</TEXT>
