<HEADLINE>
FT  02 DEC 92 / UK Company News: Write-downs leave Trafalgar below City
expectations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR ALLAN GORMLY, the new chief executive of Trafalgar House, said there was
an element of clearing the decks before reporting yesterday's full-year
results.
'We have properly taken a somewhat more conservative view of the accounts as
a result of recent management changes. It would have been surprising if we
had not looked at this in a different way.'
However, while the City expected poor results, the pre-tax loss of Pounds
30.3m for the year ended September 30 was worse than most analysts
predicted. Exceptional property write-downs of Pounds 138m were also bigger
than expected.
Of the total write-down, Pounds 70.7m was charged at operating level, Pounds
46m was reflected in results of associated companies and Pounds 21.3m was
included in the interest charge.
The loss after taxation rose to Pounds 80.6m because of the substantial
advance corporation tax write off of Pounds 40.3m. The group has not been
able to make sufficient profits to offset against its ACT.
Of the company's gross ACT surplus of Pounds 183.8m to be offset against
future UK corporation tax liabilities, Pounds 31.8m has been offset against
deferred taxation. Some Pounds 2.7m, arising from the final dividend, is
carried as a debtor in the balance sheet and the rest has been written over
to the profit and loss account over the past few years.
Exceptional write-downs and the ACT write-off reduced shareholders' funds
from Pounds 684.6m to Pounds 542.2m.
Engineering was the one bright spot. The division's operating profits rose
from Pounds 56.9m to Pounds 89.4m on increased sales of Pounds 2.4bn (Pounds
1.5bn).
Davy corporation, which Trafalgar took over last year after it ran into
severe financial difficulties converting the Emerald producer oil rig,
contributed Pounds 30m. Midland and Scottish Resources, the original
customer for the rig, is leasing it from Trafalgar for Dollars 65,000
(Pounds 43,000) per day. But MSR had failed to meet purchase conditions for
Trafalgar to pay former shareholders in Davy their second takeover payment,
totalling Pounds 54m.
Overseas orders account for more than 60 per cent of the engineering
division's Pounds 2bn order book.
The construction division suffered a fall in profits from Pounds 16.9m to
Pounds 10.1m on reduced sales of Pounds 785.8m (Pounds 928.4m).
Profits from shipping and hotels fell from Pounds 36.9m to Pounds 25.3m. The
group is still looking for a partner to help it restructure the shipping
fleet.
Trafalgar said the results should be considered in light of last year's
restated pre-tax loss of Pounds 38.5m.
See Lex
