<HEADLINE>
FT  02 DEC 92 / UK Company News: Racal back in the black with Pounds 23m -
Shares fall 17p as turnround fails to meet company's expectations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RACAL ELECTRONICS, the data communications, radio and network services
group, yesterday reported the expected turnround but not to the extent
anticipated by Sir Ernest Harrison, its chairman.
Operating profits for the half year to October 9 increased by 28 per cent to
Pounds 26.8m while at the pre-tax level a loss of Pounds 2.4m was turned
into profits of Pounds 23.1m. Sales declined 6 per cent to Pounds 448m.
The interim dividend of 1.5p is 3.4 times covered and comes from earnings
per share up from 0.28p to 5.16p.
Racal-Redac, the computer-aided design systems business, lost Pounds 3m in
the first half after appearing to be on target for break-even at the time of
the demerger of Chubb.
The data communications division produced operating profits of Pounds 4.3m
against a loss of Pounds 1.78m. This was cut on sales of Pounds 173m (Pounds
178m) and included profits for the first time of Pounds 2m from the
Government Network Services arm.
Mr David Elsbury, chief executive, said the market had to remember that data
communications always enjoyed greater volume in the second half.
Radio communications improved its margin by two percentage points to 16 per
cent. Profits were Pounds 12.5m.
Following the demerger of Chubb Security the result included interest
receivable of Pounds 4.1m, an Pounds 11.6m swing from the Pounds 7.4m charge
last year. The group also took high exceptional charges of Pounds 7.78m,
covering redundancies, although it was half the figure for the same period
last year.
Net debt was reduced by positive cash flow from a pro-forma Pounds 61.2m, at
the time of the demerger, to Pounds 59.7m after Pounds 18m of capital
expenditure.
COMMENT
While these figures were broadly in line with expectations, the market
remains concerned that Racal's biggest division, data communications, has
still not convincingly turned the corner. And Redac again disappointed,
turning in a loss where break-even was expected. Yesterday's share price
fall - down 17p to 154p - has much to do with the shaving of full-year
forecasts that this triggered and some profit taking after a strong run up
in the share price. But earnings growth is still good and the possibility of
a bid - the prize being the potential for raising data communications'
margins - still cannot be ruled out. Even with shaved full-year forecasts of
Pounds 50m, giving earnings of 11.1p, Racal is still on a slight prospective
discount to the market and good value as it started its recovery from such a
low base.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 24
</PAGE>
