<HEADLINE>
FT  02 DEC 92 / EC seeks user-friendly single market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A NETWORK of officials across each EC country will be given the task of
making the single market more user-friendly at next month's European Council
in Edinburgh.
The officials will be expected to keep in close touch with one another to
try to ensure that the single market works properly.
Many of the main subjects for discussion at the EC summit are looking
increasingly hard to resolve. But the UK government is relieved that in
trying to make the single market more user-friendly, it seems to have
carried European opinion with it.
The move will mean a sharp increase in contacts between officials as they
try to resolve issues before they are raised more formally through embassies
or in EC committees.
One aim is to sort out more readily business difficulties which arise from
misunderstandings rather than from breaches of EC law.
Mr Richard Needham, the trade minister, said: 'I'm not starry-eyed or
euphoric, but I do think that it is the substance of something that will
work.'
UK ministers and officials are conscious of the belief among British
businessmen that there will still be informal barriers to trade after the
single market comes into effect on January 1.
One minister said: 'There are going to be problems, no question. You only
have to look at the outcry here if it looks as if a foreign company is going
to get any infrastructure project.'
Nonetheless, the Department of Trade and Industry is confident that the plan
will make a significant difference in resolving practical difficulties.
A system of national co-ordinators has been established to deal with
difficulties over the mutual recognition of professional qualifications. The
new network of officials may develop similarly over a wider field.
There will also be annual discussions on how the market is working and
further efforts to agree European standards in areas where national
standards still apply.
</TEXT>
