<HEADLINE>
FT  02 DEC 92 / Report sets out an ambitious remit for self-regulation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ENORMOUS painting of Henry VIII in the Barber-Surgeon's Hall in London
hung uneasily yesterday behind the members of the Cadbury committee
preaching the message of greater power-sharing in corporate boardrooms.
After 18 months, Pounds 160,000 in expenses and countless hours of committee
time, the final version of the report on the financial aspects of corporate
governance offered an ambitious and perhaps last chance for self-regulation
to work.
At the heart of the document is the code of best practice, which encompasses
boards of directors, non-executive directors, executive directors and
reporting and controls of companies.
The annual reports of all quoted companies from June 30 next year must
include a statement saying they comply with the code, or spec-ifying any
divergence from it.
In addition to the code there is a detailed series of recommendations on
good practice which are powerful but not enforceable.
Non-executive directors: Boards will require a minimum of three
non-executive directors, at least two of whom should be independent.
When they first join, directors should be given a schedule of matters
reserved for decision by the full board, which should lay down rules to
determine any transactions that are considered material.
To ensure their independence, non-executive directors should not participate
in share-option schemes nor receive a pension from the company.
They should be selected by a nomination committee, which should have a
majority of non-executive directors and make a proposal to the board. On
appointment, non-executives should receive a letter setting out their
duties, term of office, remuneration and its review.
Board sub-committees: The remuneration committee's membership should be set
out in the directors' report, and its chairman should be available to answer
questions at the annual meeting.
Audit committees should be formally constituted as sub-committees of the
main board, be given written terms of reference and normally meet at least
twice a year. The external auditor and the head of internal audit should
attend, as should the finance director. Membership should be disclosed in
the annual report.
There should be at least one audit committee meeting with the auditors each
year - without executive board members present - to discuss any unresolved
issues of concern. It should be able to obtain outside professional advice,
and full access to information to investigate any matters within its terms
of reference. Financial reporting: The report and accounts should contain a
coherent narrative of the company's performance and prospects alongside
suitable figures. Setbacks should be dealt with as well as successes.
Directors' responsibilities: There should be a statement covering the legal
requirement for directors to prepare financial statements each year that
give a true and fair view; and their responsibility to maintain adequate
accounting records, safeguard assets of the company, prevent and detect
fraud, and consistently apply suitable accounting policies and standards.
The committee's main recommendations are:
Boards of all listed companies should comply with the code of best practice.
There should be a statement about their compliance and any reasons in areas
of non-compliance in accounts for years after June 30 1993.
The statement of compliance should be reviewed by the auditors before
publication, where the statements can be objectively verified. The Auditing
Practices Board should consider issuing guidance.
All parties concerned with corporate governance - particularly institutional
investors - should use their influence to encourage compliance. The
committee's sponsors should appoint a new committee by the end of June 1995
to examine how far there is compliance and implementation of the other
recommendations, and consider wider issues of corporate governance.
The Companies Act should be amended so directors' service contracts should
not exceed three years without shareholders' approval.
Interim accounts should include information about balance sheets and they
should be reviewed by auditors. Regulations under the 1991 Companies Act
should be reviewed to ensure the disclosure of the company's audit and
non-audit fees paid to the audit firm.
The accountancy profession should draw up guidelines on the rotation of
audit partners.
Directors should report on the effectiveness of internal controls, and the
auditors should report on that statement. The accountancy profession should
draw up criteria for assessing the systems.
Directors should state in the report and accounts that the company is a
going concern. Accountants should develop guidance on that. Legislation
should be considered to back reporting on internal controls.
The government should consider extending to auditors of all companies the
protection given to those in the regulated sector so they can report
reasonable suspicion of fraud freely to the authorities.
The accountancy profession should consider the question of illegal acts
other than fraud, and how to improve standards and procedures to strengthen
the standing and independence of auditors.
Institutional investors should disclose their policies on the use of their
voting rights. The committee's successor body should consider issues
including the application of the code to smaller listed companies;
directors' training; disclosure of directors' remuneration; the inclusion of
cashflow information in interim reports; procedures for putting forward
resolutions at general meetings; and developments on the nature and extent
of auditors' liability.
The Financial Aspects of Corporate Governance. Gee, South Quay Plaza, 183
Marsh Wall, London E14 9FS. Pounds 10.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 12
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-4486</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CLBBRACHFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921202
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 DEC 92 / Reservations underlie welcome for Cadbury
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS, MICHAEL CASSELL and ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE was almost universal support throughout the City and the UK's
boardrooms yesterday for the final Cadbury report on the way companies are
run - at least on the surface. Underneath, however, there remained nagging
concerns, particularly from companies.
Mr Charles Nunnelly, managing director of Robert Fleming Asset Management,
said: 'You can't be against it. You have to be for it.
'The danger is that while the reaction is lovely and warm, no one will do
anything about it.'
The warm words - flavoured with disaffection about the way the report might
interfere with the relationship between companies and shareholders - were in
abundant supply yesterday. They could even be heard coming from the
Confederation of British Industry, which previously condemned the
requirement for companies to comply with the Cadbury code of conduct as a
condition of a Stock Exchange listing. Yesterday the CBI toned down its
criticisms.
An official said: 'A code of best practice which can be reviewed and updated
is better than wholesale intrusion by the law, which would be inflexible and
slow to change. Moreover, the report makes it clear that individuals and
companies will need to follow the code in the light of their own
circumstances.'
The Institute of Directors, which had also voiced criticism of the draft
report, gave its 'strong support' to the final document, which it said went
a long way to meeting the organisation's reservations.
Mr Peter Morgan, IoD director-general, said the original emphasis on the
separate roles of executive and non-executive directors had damaged the
belief in unitary boards. He said most concern had been largely allayed by
the tempering of 'divisive proposals' concerning non-executive directors.
The IoD backed the statement of compliance and, like the CBI, welcomed the
committee's decision to restrict the remit of auditors in reviewing the code
of compliance, although it warned that the audit function would place a
'particularly heavy burden' on smaller quoted companies.
Mr Morgan said the committee's recommendations, with the development of new
accounting standards, would help to restore falling public confidence in
corporate governance.
Institutional investors, meanwhile, were also generally happy that
recommendations they had made after the interim report appeared to have been
taken up in the final version. The Institutional Shareholders' Committee,
the umbrella body representing various groupings of investors, said it would
meet to discuss its reaction within a fortnight, but there were signs
yesterday that its members welcomed the new paper.
The National Association of Pension Funds said: 'We will play our part and
encourage our members to play their part as well.' It said it believed in
the division of responsibility between chairmen and chief executives of
public companies, and would continue to press for a strict separation of the
two roles.
Institutional investors also appeared happier to take on a more central role
in enforcing the code of conduct. 'I think that's fair enough. From our
point of view, we try to stand up and do our bit,' said Mr Barry Southcote
of CIN, investment manager for the Coal industry pension funds.
There was general support for the new recommendation that investment
managers should disclose their policy on voting at companies' annual
meetings - although several pointed out that this could cause difficulties
for fund managers who needed shareholder approval before voting.
While the debate on corporate governance is the topic of the moment, it may
have little impact in the long term. As Mr Roger Davis, head of audit at
Coopers &amp; Lybrand, said: 'The great pity is that corporate governance is a
cyclical activity. It's topical now, but in a recession mavericks lie low.'
</TEXT>
