FT  02 DEC 92 / Building industry calls for rate cut
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A CUT IN interest rates of a further 1 percentage point is needed to
stimulate recovery in the construction industry and to prevent further job
losses, the government was warned last night, Andrew Taylor writes.
Sir Brian Hill, president of the Building Employers Confederation, the
industry's biggest trade association, said: 'The construction industry faces
a long haul before output reaches a level where the rise in unemployment
will first be checked and then reversed.'
Sir Brian was speaking at the confederation's annual dinner in London. He
added: 'Another cut in interest rates of 1 per cent would provide a further
vital component in the government's engine for growth.'
More than 400,000 jobs are estimated to have been lost in the industry since
the summer of 1989. Company failures, job losses and plant closures are
expected to continue, even if construction output stops falling next year.
Sir Brian said the housing market needed improving if the economy was to
recover and people were to be encouraged to start buying consumer goods
again.
In spite of government measures announced in the Autumn Statement, there
remained significant anxiety about housing. Barely 800,000 house sales are
expected this year, compared with 1.3m a year in the 1980s.
</TEXT>
