<HEADLINE>
FT  02 DEC 92 / Pellerin Cezannes sell well: Saleroom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SUSAN MOORE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SEVEN Cezannes from the collection formed by Auguste Pellerin went under the
hammer at Christie's in London on Monday evening. All of them sold - one
immediately after the sale - almost all at the lower end of their published
estimates.
Only 'L'Homme a la Pipe', the most impressive of this important but uneven
group, exceeded expectations by selling for Pounds 3.52m. It is the only
surviving study for the figure of the pipe-smoking spectator who features in
the monumental Cardplayers series.
A fiercely expressive self-portrait, which once belonged to the artist's
friend, the novelist Emile Zola, tipped Pounds 1m. What was hailed as the
star turn, a painting of five male bathers, fetched Pounds 3.025m.
Pellerin was one of the earliest and most passionate collectors of Cezanne.
Between 1895 and 1925 he amassed more than 100 works by the master - many
now hang in leading museums.
The sale demonstrates that there is still demand for exceptional works of
art - particularly those with a distinguished provenance. It also witnesses
a new discrimination among buyers.
A watercolour drawing of another of Cezanne's favourite motifs, the Mont
Sainte-Victoire, also sold well, realising Pounds 1.43m. A large oil and
distemper 'intimiste' interior by Vuillard made Pounds 1.54m.
</TEXT>
