FT  02 DEC 92 / Parliament and Politics: PM 'was unaware' of Matrix probe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR John Major emphasised yesterday that he had been unaware of the
government's investigation into exports of machine tools to Iraq by Matrix
Churchill until after the invasion of Kuwait, Philip Stephens writes.
In a parliamentary answer to Mr George Robertson, the Labour foreign affairs
spokesman, Mr Major said he was first told of the investigation in October
1990.
The prime minister also revealed that Mr Richard Ryder, now the chief whip,
had been the Treasury's representative at a ministerial meeting in July 1990
that decided to relax the guidelines restricting defence-related sales to
Iraq. Mr Major said his preoccupation at that time as chancellor was with
the annual public-spending negotiations.
His answer said he had seen a minute in August 1990 referring to Matrix
Churchill but he had 'no recollection' of seeing earlier papers copied to
the Treasury referring to the company's activities.
The implication of the answer - although it was not spelt out in the reply -
was that as foreign secretary during 1989 he had not seen any papers
relating to the exports.
