<HEADLINE>
FT  02 DEC 92 / Parliament and Politics: Maastricht debate dominated by
treaty's critics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY and IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MPS SETTLED into the marathon debate over the detailed provisions of the
Maastricht treaty legislation in the Commons last night at a pace that will
please the Euro-sceptics and confirm the worst fears of those seeking an
early agreement.
Insisting on painstaking attention to procedure and detail, the treaty's
opponents dominated the floor from the outset, taking the first hour and 32
minutes entirely on points of order.
But MPs were assured a relatively early finish on this first day of the
committee stage, when the government chose not to force a trial of strength
by moving that the debate continue beyond 10pm.
When proceedings wound up on the stroke of ten, Mr Bill Cash, the arch Tory
Euro-sceptic was still speaking, having risen nearly two-and-a-half hours
earlier. A Conservative whip provoked mass hilarity by formally reporting
'the committee has made progress.'
Of the 45 initial interventions, barely half a dozen were from supporters of
the bill. Several prominent anti-Maastricht MPs - including Mr Bill Cash, Mr
Tony Marlow, and Sir Teddy Taylor spoke three times. Mr Nicholas Budgen, a
key critic of the treaty, topped the scoring with five interventions.
Both Labour and Tory MPs repeatedly sought clarification from the chair as
to how they could ensure that the Commons was given the right to debate
whether a referendum might be held on the treaty.
Arguing for a referendum amendment to be taken, Sir Teddy Taylor said: 'I
fear that this bill has been drafted in such a way as to prevent members of
the House of Commons in expressing a view.'
Government claims to have isolated Britain from any federalist developments
in the European Community were disputed by both supporters and opponents of
the treaty.
Mr Tristan Garel-Jones, foreign office minister in charge of the European
Communities (Amendment) Bill which seeks to embody some provisions of the
treaty in UK domestic law, was caught in a withering crossfire from the
government and opposition benches.
Sir Russell Johnston, spokesman for the Liberal Democrats and an
enthusiastic advocate of a federalist Europe, urged the government to drop
its attempt to disguise the federal implications of the treaty.
He moved an amendment seeking to include in the bill a provision of the
treaty which the government had deliberately excluded.
Mr Bernard Jenkin (C Colchester North) asked: 'Are you suggesting that the
government is seeking to sell the treaty on a somewhat false prospectus?'.
After a momentary hesitation Sir Russell replied: 'I can pretty nearly say
yes.'
He repudiated ministerial assertions that the inclusion of the so-called
subsidiarity principle had strengthened the position of national governments
and parliaments. Sir Russell insisted that the majority of Britain's
community partners took a 'significantly' different view of subsidiarity
believing it to be an instrument for use in a federalist structure.
Euro-sceptics on the Tory backbenches agreed with Mr Tony Benn (Lab
Chesterfield), a consistent opponent of Britain's membership of the EC, that
by omitting some provisions of the treaty from the bill the government was
hoping to prevent the British people knowing the 'enormity' of what was
involved.
Mr Garel-Jones maintained that the purpose of the bill was to bring into
British law those elements of the Maastricht treaty not involving amendment
of the Treaty of Rome under which the EC was established.
He appealed to Sir Russell to withdraw his amendment.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
