<HEADLINE>
FT  02 DEC 92 / Parliament and Politics: Labour-union link strained
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Labour party's relations with the trade unions came under further strain
yesterday, with the AEEU craft union's dissent against the outline final
report of the party committee reviewing union links. It said it would, if
necessary, produce a minority report to the National Executive Committee.
Mr Nigel Harris, the AEEU official who sits on the union links committee,
said the union strongly objected to dropping the idea of one-member-one-vote
for the election of leader and deputy leader and for the selection of
parliamentary candidates.
The union links committee report instead backed the idea of a new category
of 'registered supporter' - union members who want to do more than pay the
political levy but do not want to be full members - who would have a role in
the elections for the leadership and for local candidates.
That idea is backed by several members of the committee, by the GMB general
union and Nupe the public-services union, and by senior Labour party
officials.
Mr Harris said it was unworkable and undemocratic. He also said it would
revive the spectre of 'entryism' and provide ammunition for Conservatives
who are keen to force unions to change to a system of 'contracting in' to
the political levy.
Mr Harris said that several other members of the committee, including Mr
Tony Blair, shadow home secretary, rejected the idea of registered
supporters and also pointed to the public support for one-member-one-vote
from Mr John Smith, the party leader.
The issue threatens to create a new fault-line within the party, but a new
draft of the final report due to be presented to another meeting of the
links committee today is unlikely to include any fundamental change.
Mr Harris says, though, that if the final report, to be sent to the NEC in
January, does not include the option of one-member-one-vote, those who
support the idea will produce a minority report.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 10
</PAGE>
