<HEADLINE>
FT  02 DEC 92 / Parliament and Politics: Shephard firm on Tec funds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DIFFICULTIES in imple-menting the government's guarantee of a job or a
training place for all school leavers arose from a lack of capacity among
employers in some areas and not lack of central funding, Mrs Gillian
Shephard, employment secretary, told the Commons yesterday.
Insisting that there was no shortage of resources, she said they were
sufficient to provide 244,000 places while demand was estimated at 216,000.
Mrs Shephard said she had written to Mr Ron Leighton, the Labour chairman of
the Commons employment committee, explaining how the guarantee was being
met.
Miss Joan Lestor (Lab Eccles), highlighted the difficulties caused in
implementing the guarantee in the Salford area by the growing number of
company failures.
When Mr Stephen Milligan (C Eastleigh) said 1,000 people in Hampshire were
unable to get a training place, Mrs Shephard acknowledged the difficulty
faced by employers in some areas.
'They will be helped to meet the guarantee by the end of this month,' she
said.
Mrs Shephard also emphasised that there was always a 'surge of demand' in
the autumn, when young people sought training places.
Reaffirming that the government stood by the guarantee, she said adequate
resources were available to training and enterprise councils (Tecs) and
their Scottish equivalents (Lecs). She undertook to examine any complaints
that adequate funds were not available and said the local initiative fund
which allowed Tecs and Lecs to develop new ideas in support of training and
business growth would be increased by Pounds 12m in 1993-94.
</TEXT>
