<HEADLINE>
FT  02 DEC 92 / Labour doubts on sale of PSA arm to Tarmac
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR YESTERDAY expressed concern over the sale of the Property Services
Agency's projects division to Tarmac, the construction and building
materials group.
Mr Doug Henderson, a local-government spokesman, has tabled a series of
parliamentary questions requesting details of any meetings that may have
taken place between Tarmac and the PSA board before the sale took place.
The issue has arisen because of concern about what the government agreed to
pay Tarmac to take over the projects division, which had a number of problem
contracts and was in danger of closure.
Mr Henderson said in a letter to Mr Michael Howard, the environment
secretary, that the government had disclosed that Tarmac had been paid or
guaranteed Pounds 120m of public money to take over the division.
He requested information on whether an additional Pounds 130m had been
promised to Tarmac in settlement of disputes arising from the construction
of the Trident base at Faslane, in Scotland and Howell Grange Prison in
Leeds.
Tarmac said that the responsibility for managing the Trident contract had
been left with the Ministry of Defence as part of the sale agreement. Any
settlement, therefore, would be the responsibility of ministry and not
Tarmac.
It also denied that it would receive Pounds 120m from the purchase. It said
that that had been made clear in a parliamentary answer given Mr John
Redwood, environment minister, on November 25.
'Initially we will receive Pounds 54.9m to cover unpaid bills owed by the
PSA and to meet the cost of putting the business on a commercial footing. A
further Pounds 10m to Pounds 20m could be paid to cover contingencies such
as redundancies for some of the workers taken on under the sale.'
Confusion has arisen because the government also has to meet the cost of
redundancies of former PSA workers who have not been taken on by Tarmac. The
company will take on 850 of the division's 1,900 workers.
The cost of redundancies of workers not employed by Tarmac has been
estimated by Mr Redwood at between Pounds 30m to Pounds 35m. In addition,
the government has agreed to guarantee future redundancy payments of former
PSA workers in the unlikely event of Tarmac going bust in the next five
years.
Ministers have also agreed to provide money to bring pension-fund benefits
for former employees in line with what they would have received if they had
remained in the public sector.
Tarmac emphasised that none of that money would be coming to the group and
was entirely the responsibility of government.
</TEXT>
