<HEADLINE>
FT  02 DEC 92 / Forecast of Lloyd's US losses attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SENIOR UNDERWRITERS at Lloyd's of London have described independent
estimates of the insurance market's potential losses from liabilities for US
pollution and industrial diseases as 'grossly misleading', Richard Lapper
writes.
Chatset, the company that analyses Lloyd's results, said on Tuesday that it
might cost Lloyd's Pounds 5.3bn to settle claims on the market's 162 'open
years' - which occur when a syndicate cannot close its accounts because of
uncertainty about future claims.
Mr Richard Youell, an underwriter, said Chatset's assessment of his own
syndicate's open year of 1989 was 'wholly contrary to our views on the
syndicate's future development'.
Mr David Foster, of the Lloyd's pollution committee, said Chatset's figures
had 'no scientific basis'.
</TEXT>
