<HEADLINE>
FT  02 DEC 92 / Eurotunnel warns it may sue over rail privatisation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR Alastair Morton, chief executive of Eurotunnel, yesterday warned that
his company would consider suing the government if railway privatisation cut
the amount of rail traffic expected to use the Channel tunnel.
Sir Alastair said he feared that the privatisation plans in their present
form were in danger of driving rail freight on to the roads and cutting the
investment needed to build new lines.
The result was likely to be less rail freight going through the Channel
tunnel and insufficient capacity for increases in the number of Channel
tunnel expresses, so cutting Eurotunnel's revenues.
Sir Alastair was speaking in advance of today's meeting of the Commons
transport committee, where he is due to appear as a witness on railway
privatisation.
He said Eurotunnel would hold the government liable if its revenues suffered
through changes in the conditions under which the Channel tunnel concession
agreement was drawn up in 1986.
Since privatisation was not on the government's agenda in 1986, that
constituted a change in conditions - and Sir Alastair said he was convinced
the effects would be adverse.
Although British Rail and SNCF, the French national railway, have undertaken
to buy 50 per cent of the Channel tunnel's capacity, part of the fees
Eurotunnel receives will depend on how many trains pass through and how much
they carry.
Sir Alastair said BR's plans to create a track-owning body and to introduce
track charges for freight and passenger trains would price most freight
traffic off the rails.
He also feared that privatisation would lead to a fall in railway
investment, so worsening the prospects of action to relieve the capacity
shortage on railway lines to and from the tunnel.
</TEXT>
