<HEADLINE>
FT  02 DEC 92 / 'Bolshevik' leads capitalist revolution: 'Let them eat cake'
becomes rallying cry of Russia's privatisation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A PASTRY-MAKING company called 'Bolshevik' will be among the first to point
the way to the privatised economy, Russian officials said yesterday.
It will be one of six large companies to be put on the market this month to
provide an example to citizens of how to use their Rbs10,000 privatisation
vouchers, expected to be distributed to all by the end of the year.
Some 5,000 big enterprises, worth an estimated Rbs1,500bn are to be sold off
from January 1, according to Mr Anatoly Chubais, the deputy prime minister
in charge of privatisation. Mr Dmitri Vasiliev, deputy head of the
privatisation committee, said yesterday that 'it's hard to tell whether the
(enterprises) are future giants or if they're bankrupt, because of the
unstable situation in the market'.
However, the first large enterprises will come to the market within two
weeks in Moscow, St Petersburg, Vladivostok in the Far East and Perm in the
Urals. They have been carefully prepared by the government and foreign
advisers. The most famous, for Russians, is Bolshevik, a 2,200-employee
cake-maker which makes some of the sweetest products on the market.
Mr Oleg Shumanov, Bolshevik's managing director, said the workers and
management had chosen to privatise their company by taking 51 per cent of
the shares - with the remainder being offered for auction to citizens for
their vouchers. The company has been working with Credit Suisse First Boston
on a system which will allow voucher holders to come to a Moscow sales
centre from December 9 to apply for shares - the price of which will be set
by demand.
Mr Boris Jordan, a CSFB executive in Moscow, said Bolshevik had been chosen
for its brand recognition, its size, the fact that it was in Moscow and its
enthusiasm to be privatised.
Together with the other plants, the experience of the sale of Bolshevik will
be analysed for use in the mass privatisations by the government in
consultation with its financial advisers.
</TEXT>
