<HEADLINE>
FT  02 DEC 92 / BBC's finance chief to leave next year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Ian Phillips, the BBC director of finance, is to leave the corporation at
the end of February.
Announcement of the departure comes a few days before the BBC governors are
expected to publish a detailed report on a serious projected overspend at
BBC television.
The BBC has admitted that the possible overspend is about Pounds 20m. The
final figure, however, is likely to be as high as Pounds 60m.
The corporation said last night that Mr Phillips, who is 54, was leaving the
corporation to 'pursue a range of other activities'. It insisted that it was
'pure coincidence' that the announcement of Mr Phillips' departure and
publication of the report occurred at about the same time.
The report is being produced by a governors' audit committee chaired by Lord
Barnett, vice-chairman of the governors and a former chief secretary to the
Treasury.
Senior figures at the BBC declined to comment further on the reason for Mr
Phillips' unexpected departure. Mr Phillips, who joined the corporation in
1988 from the British Railways Board, would have had responsibility for the
finances of the corporation but would not have been in day-to-day charge of
the finances of BBC television.
The signs are that Lord Barnett has been conducting a thorough investigation
of the reasons for the possible overspend, which has apparently been caused
by a number of factors coinciding, such as over-optimism on co-production
revenues and the transition costs of moving towards 'producer choice'. This
is the system allowing producers to buy services from outside the BBC.
The financial problems come at an embarrassing time for the BBC. It launched
its policy for the future last week, following the government's green paper
on the BBC. Both documents emphasised the importance of efficiency in the
BBC's handling of licence payers' money.
Christopher Dunkley, Page 19
</TEXT>
