FT  01 DEC 92 / Tyne &amp; Wear steel strikers reject deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WORKERS at a steelrolling mill at Gateshead, Tyne and Wear, yesterday
rejected a deal to end a five-month strike.
Production at Spartan Redheugh, part of GM Firth, the steel stockholding
group, has been at a standstill since July when management took steps to
sweep away a bonus system it described as 'archaic' and introduce more
flexible working practices.
The strikers, members of the AEEU electricians' and engineering workers'
union and the Iron and Steel Trades Confederation, claim they were faced
with pay cuts of up to 25 per cent. Acrimony increased when the company
advertised for a new manual workforce. Nobody has so far been recruited.
The proposed package of terms and conditions was negotiated between the
unions and management with help from Acas, the conciliation service. The
strikers said they had rejected the proposal because it would mean 45
redundancies and included unacceptable preconditions.
Mr Peter Scarff, director of operations at Spartan Redheugh, said the plan
would have meant no more than 15 redundancies and would have given the
manual workforce a minimum wage of Pounds 6.50 per hour. In exchange the
company wanted to introduce new working practices, he said. Union officials
are understood to have believed that the package was the best obtainable.
