<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (20): Towards the new Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PRABHU GUPTARA
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EUROPEAN CORPORATE STRATEGY: HEADING FOR 2000
by Oliver L Landreth
Macmillan Press, Pounds 35
THE KEY corporate battleground is now clearly that of Europe. Politicians
hum and haw about the political and monetary future of Europe, but its
economic future is already being shaped to a substantial extent by company
policies and processes.
The question of what strategies companies should follow has been the subject
of academic treatises since the Single Market appeared on the horizon. What
strategies companies are following is the question this book investigates.
Landreth selects nine companies from the industrial, services and consumer
goods sectors, originating from all over Europe (Portugal and Italy in the
south, Scandinavia in the north). There is also a chapter on how the
European truck manufacturing industry is being restructured. The two largest
and best-known companies profiled are CMB Packaging and SAS: middle-sized
companies are the focus, though the lessons drawn from these cases apply
even to the largest multinationals.
What are the challenges and opportunities for European companies? First, the
elimination of traditional competitive advantages, such as protected access
to technology and markets; then, ever-more sophisticated and
internationally-oriented consumers. Internally, companies need to improve
logistics, consolidate brand image, centralise R&amp;D, and promote innovation
on a Europe-wide and indeed global basis. Contrarily, there is the challenge
of handling cultural diversity and attempting product customisation.
Landreth does not go as far as his research should take him, and continues
to talk about the need for 'clearly-defined country strategies . . . (and)
national sales, service and distribution plans': if these do not already
exist, there is not much hope for any company; but, on the other hand, these
national groupings will increasingly be replaced by language-groupings. The
book is also marred by its prose, which is neither stylish nor clear:
'Economies of scale are now being acquired through mergers and acquisitions,
as are the effects of the learning curve.'
However, because Landreth has not followed the usual path of studying only
Fortune 500 type companies, he has put together an unusual book which will
be useful to a wide range of companies.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page X
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-4609</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CLACAAGSFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921201
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (21): Barriers in
accountancy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ACCOUNTING HARMONISATION IN EUROPE, VOLUME II
by Christopher Nobes
Financial Times Business Information, Pounds 160
IF BRITISH standards-setters had bothered to glance across the English
Channel a few years ago before they started investigating an approach to
replacement cost accounting, they could have saved themselves considerable
trouble: Philips, the electronics group based in the Netherlands, had
already developed a version which it had been using in its published annual
accounts since 1951.
The incident is just one example of the many differences and barriers to
change in financial reporting and auditing standards across Europe,
highlighted in Christopher Nobes' book on EC accounting harmonisation.
There are many ways of classifying accounting patterns in the EC states,
says Nobes, professor of accounting at Reading University, and a committee
member of the Federation of European Accountants.
One clear-cut distinction is between the so-called Anglo-Saxon model -
including the UK, Ireland, the US, Canada, Australia and the Netherlands -
and the Continental model - such as France, Germany, Spain, Italy, Japan and
Greece. The Anglo-Saxon countries tend to use English law, have a
significant equity market, and a strong, long-established accountancy
profession.  The Continental versions are very different. The former are
oriented towards shareholders, disclosure, professional standards and
substance over form in printed accounts; the latter play towards creditors,
are tax-dominated and enshrined in law.
In a useful review of current legislation, he shows how EC company law
directives are bringing about changes while still leaving room for great
differences in presentation, measurement, publication and audit.
There are some frustrations with the book. While he tantalisingly touches on
the fall of the Iron Curtain and the westernisation of former the Communist
countries at the start, Nobes does not explore how financial reporting
practice is developing. He is also not always entirely sure whether his
function is to provide a textbook or a rather more opinionated commentary.
But the result is a valuable introduction to a topic which receives far too
little serious consideration.
</TEXT>
