<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (22): Scotland the different
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ANATOMY OF SCOTLAND
Edited by Magnus Linklater and Robin Denniston
Chambers, Pounds 15.99 431 pages
THE NICE THING about Scotland is its manageable size. Its population is
concentrated, with 4m of its 5m people living in the 70-mile-long central
belt. Its principal companies and its institutions, financial and otherwise,
are few. for You frequently go to gatherings at which a good selection of
the top people in the country are all together.
Above all, Scotland is different. Scots feel themselves to be a distinct
nation within the UK and do many things differently from England. Scotland
therefore lends itself to a book like this, which describes the different
sectors of public life in the country, its distinctive organisations and
economy.
The editors, Magnus Linklater, editor of The Scotsman, and Robin Denniston,
a publisher, also promise to tell how the country 'works,' who runs it and
how those people exercise their power.
The title emulates Anthony Sampson's famous Anatomy of Britain which first
appeared in 1962. Like Sampson's book, this has chapters on such things as
the law, the aristocracy, politics, the civil service, the church, business,
economic quangos, the arts and sport.
It is all useful stuff, fascinating and entertaining in parts, and the book
should be on the shelf of anyone who needs to know about Scotland. It is
remarkably free of inaccuracies, the sub-section on the financial community
being an exception.
But unlike Sampson's Anatomy of Britain this book is written by ten authors,
mostly Scottish journalists such as George Rosie, Alf Young or Peter Jones.
This is not the exploration of an outsider who comes in to meet the key
people but rather the view of writers with distilled knowledge of their
subject.
As a result there is no overall judgment on Scotland, its strengths,
weaknesses or its future, and the broad questions posed by the editors never
really receive an answer. How is that a country with a very small ruling
group (perhaps only about 2,000 people, many of whom appear fleetingly in
this book) rarely succeeds in defining a big objective, then combining to
achieve it? Scots often express their frustration at this.
Linklater says in his introduction that although the lines of influence of
leading Scots 'cross and criss-cross,' it is hard to talk about a Scottish
'Establishment.' England, he thinks, has a much more obvious ruling class.
He may be right (I disagree) but in a book on how Scotland works it deserve
more than a paragraph.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
