<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (18): Jobs for the boys -
for life
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WOMEN AND JAPANESE MANAGEMENT: DISCRIMINATION AND REFORM
by Alice Lam
Routledge, Pounds 35, 240 pages
IT WOULD NOT be difficult for a stranger to Japan to discern that there is
widespread discrimination against women in the Japanese working environment.
It is not so much that women employees in Japanese companies are ill-treated
in such an obvious way that might attract widespread criticism. The
discrimination is so subtle and so ingrained in the Japanese way of life
that those who are guilty of discriminating against women are quite likely
to be unaware of the crime.
Alice Lam does well to identify the socio-cultural roots of this
discrimination in Japanese management practices in her study. Dr Lam, who
spent several years in Japan studying the role of women in Japanese
corporations, points out that women have long provided a convenient and
flexible workforce in a country where the rigid demands of lifetime
employment practices place considerable pressures on corporations when
changes in the economic climate call for expansion or reduction of the
labour force.
She also rightly pronounces that despite the introduction of the Equal
Employment Opportunity Law in 1985, and recurring prophesies of the eventual
collapse of the traditional employment system in Japan, things have not
really changed that much.
Women are still mainly employed in specialised areas or for specific
purposes, such as to identify and develop products likely to appeal to
housewives. They are still employed in such a way that the male-dominated
management system of lifetime male employment can be perpetuated.
The introduction at some Japanese companies of a career conversion system,
whereby women in clerical positions are given an opportunity to apply to the
managerial career route, itself 'formally legitimises total segregation of
men and women.' Even for the most ambitious and dedicated women employees,
the importance of informal clique networks and patronage by senior staff,
who will invariably be male, create strong barriers to advancement.
Dr Lam concludes that in order to further improve women's position in the
Japanese labour market and bring equal the country's opportunity standards
to the level commonly accepted in the west, 'major legal reforms and
stronger policy interventions are necessary.'
The book is a rich source of information not only on the conditions for
women in Japanese corporations but also on Japanese management practices in
general.
Unfortunately, the dry, academic style Dr Lam employs is likely to
discourage many prospective readers. Although it may not have been
appropriate for the academic study which Dr Lam has written, a few anecdotes
would have helped to enliven the narrative. It is also a disappointment that
Dr Lam has not really discussed the issue of sexual harassment which is a
real, though difficult to identify, phenomenon in a male-dominated
environment. However, for the student not only of Japanese management but of
women's studies generally, the book offers some helpful insights.
Dr Lam concludes that: 'If Japanese women are to achieve full and real
equality, it cannot be on men's terms. The male work norm will have to be
changed and the Japanese management system will need to be challenged.' The
same could be said for women in even the most liberal societies.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IX
</PAGE>
