<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (17): Virtually all the
answers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL THOMPSON-NOEL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE VIRTUAL CORPORATION
by William H Davidow and Michael S Malone
HarperBusiness, Dollars 23, 294 pages
LIFE CYCLES, MONEY CYCLES
by Patricia Lynch
John Wiley &amp; Sons Dollars 19.95,
270 pages
SUCCESSFUL TEAM BUILDING
by John Davis, Peter Millburn, Terry Murphy, Martin Woodhouse
Kogan Page, Pounds 17.95, 184 pages
DEALING WITH DIFFICULT PEOPLE
by Roberta Cava
Piatkus Books, Pounds 8.95, 182 pages
PART of the corporate hangover of the 1980s is the immense quantity of
business books now cluttering bookshops and airport bookstalls. Many must
have been planned and commissioned in the late 1980s, which is one good
reason for regarding them with a healthily jaundiced eye. If these guys are
such hot shots, if capitalism and corporate management are so accessible and
describable - how come we're in the mess we're in?
At a guess, the amount of harm done to companies by stuff printed in
business books must be colossal. The trouble is: how can you know which
managers or underlings have been indoctrinated by which version of which
cock-eyed theory or numbskull extrapolation? Answer comes there none.
Not that I would stop anyone reading The Virtual Corporation, which is
subtitled Structuring and Revitalising the Corporation for the 21st Century.
It has strong entertainment value. It may even be sensible. For a start, it
should appeal to all sci-fi fans - a broad church, numbered in millions -
while its general approach is excitingly pre-millennial.
'Virtual' corporations, we learn, will sell 'virtual' products and services,
defined as those that adapt in real time to customers' changing needs.
Typically, customers will participate in the design and creation of what
they buy.
We are talking 'co-destiny' relationships between corporations of the 21st
century and their suppliers, distributors and retailers. We are talking
commitment to do almost anything necessary to keep customers for life. We
are talking new, flattened corporate organisational profiles that eliminate
middle management and greatly empower line-workers.
With luck, several thousand chief executives will read this book, shudder,
bang themselves between the eyes - and start to raise their games.
They can skip Life Cycles, Money Cycles. It is said to be aimed at the
'beginning investor,' and to contain unique and useful insights. True, there
are spots of good advice. One of them: beware stockbrokers' recommendations.
'At best, a broker's advice is no better than your own good judgment.'
Possibly that is true. But the book contains so much unintended humour that
you may have to ask for it at the comedy counter.
Not so Successful Team Building, which is abysmally po-faced and likely to
interest only the most wretched tiers of middle management: the folk who
will be swept from the building about seven years from now if The Virtual
Corporation knows what it is talking about.
Conversely, I enjoyed Dealing With Difficult People. I have been called a
prima donna, though on weasely, scatterbrained evidence. Be that as it may,
this book has vaulted me two steps ahead in the corporate rat race. Now I
know why I am difficult. And I know how to deal with me.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IX
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-4615</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CLACAAGMFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921201
