<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (16): A small stick to beat
them
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VICTOR MALLET
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UGLY JAPANESE: NIPPON'S ECONOMIC EMPIRE IN ASIA
by Friedemann Bartu
Longman Singapore Publishers (Pte), SDollars 29.90, 287 pages. UK rep.
Longman Group UK
THOSE WHO instinctively recoil from Japan-bashing would probably do well to
remember how in 1990 Nicholas Ridley, then a Conservative minister, was
vilified for a public bout of German-bashing, and how today - after the
humiliating retreat of sterling before the Bundesbank and an outbreak of
fascist demonstrations in Germany - even his critics concede that he had a
point.
Like Germany in Europe, Japan in south-east Asia is a formidable economic
power and its expansionist 20th century history conjures up images of
wartime atrocities in the minds of the region's elder statesmen.
This year, for the first time since the war, Tokyo has sent Japanese troops
abroad, to serve with the UN peacekeeping force in Cambodia. The mission is
being undertaken with caution and reluctance, but Japan's persistent refusal
to apologise for, or in many cases even acknowledge, its imperial adventures
in Asia has angered Asians from Korea to Singapore.
On the economic side, the flood of Japanese investment into south-east Asia
since the mid-1980s by companies relocating their factories in response to
the rise of the yen has been crucial for the success of the region's
export-led economic growth.
Bartu argues that 'the Ugly Japanese' - a phrase coined by an unusually
frank Japanese diplomat - has replaced 'the Ugly American' in the role of
loud-mouthed, high-spending tourist and would-be economic and cultural
imperialist.
The increasingly visible Japanese presence in south-east Asia certainly
means that the strategies of Japanese governments, the intentions of
Japanese corporations and the reactions of non-Japanese Asians are fruitful
subjects for investigation; by the time I was nine pages into the book I had
already heard two advertisements on Thai radio for Japanese department
stores in Bangkok.
But Bartu, the economic and financial correspondent of the Swiss newspaper
Neue Zurcher Zeitung, who describes himself as 'a strong believer in the
power of 'karma', has failed to find enough anti-Japanese ammunition to
match the book's dramatic title or to satisfy the aspiring Japan-basher.
Most of the sticks with which he beats the Japanese in this anecdotal survey
of Japan in Asia are old ones and could equally be applied to their
commercial competitors: the language of Japanese business, he writes
scathingly, is the language of war and conquest, but Bartu himself later
volunteers the statement that both western and Japanese managers are
'warriors competing in a global market'; he describes transfer pricing as
'this old Japanese trick' as if it were unknown to European or US companies.
He deplores the use of foreign aid for commercial advantage, as if it were a
form of leverage exerted only by the Japanese, and provides a fascinating
account of how Japan and NEC fought dirty to win a big telecommunications
contract in Indonesia. Yet at the same time he suggests that the US fought
back to help AT&amp;T by secretly tapping high-level telephone conservations
about the contract between Tokyo and Jakarta.
Bartu damns the Japanese in south-east Asia for working too hard, and then
damns them for playing golf. There is not enough space for golf in Japan, he
says, so 'the Japanese should collect stamps and play table tennis, mahjong
or chequers.'
In spite of the occasional gratuitous insult Bartu is ultimately defeated in
his attempt to sustain an anti-Japanese polemic by his own fair-mindedness.
He tries to show that south-east Asia is drifting into the Japanese sphere
of influence, but concedes that Japanese cultural influence is 'remarkably
shallow'; he tries to portray the Japanese businessman as a ruthless samurai
warrior, but ends up feeling sorry for the lonely Japanese husband who has
left his family in Tokyo.
Wading through his 20kg of newspaper cuttings on the Japanese in Asia, Bartu
allows himself to be diverted into such intriguing but peripheral topics as
the rise of Japanese feminism, leaving too little space for serious analysis
of his central theme.
The reader is left wanting to know more about the notorious reluctance of
Japanese companies to transfer technology to south-east Asia or to promote
locals to senior management positions (there is a good chapter on the
evolution of Mitsubishi's Proton Saga car factory in Malaysia), more about
the challenge to Japanese dominance being mounted by investors from Taiwan
and Korea, and more about the consequences of Japan's failure to provide
leadership on issues such as the environment, human rights and world trade
negotiations.
Bartu concludes lamely that Asians do not want to be forced into a Pax
Japonica, but acknowledges that this a concept for which 'even most Japanese
themselves are still ill-prepared'. If the Japanese are indeed ugly, the
case is not yet proven.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IX
</PAGE>
