<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (14): The engagement of
money and finance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAMBERT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NEW PALGRAVE DICTIONARY OF MONEY AND FINANCE
Edited by Peter Newman, Murray Milgate and John Eatwell
The Macmillan Press, Pounds 350 for three-volume set
A GOOD NEW dictionary must fulfil three functions. It should inform, it
should entertain, and it should stimulate new ideas by the freshness of its
presentation and approach. The New Palgrave Dictionary of Money &amp; Finance, a
three-volume heavyweight checking in at more than 2,500 pages, scores highly
on the first two counts, and rather less certainly on the third.
In the short time that it has been on my shelves, I have startled strangers
with the depth of my recently acquired knowledge about the history of the
Federal Reserve System. I have politely corrected a normally much better
informed colleague about the record of the Super Bowl stock market
predictor. I have found the answer to questions about the workings of
monetary policy which I was too embarrassed to ask 20 years ago.
The dictionary is built round more than 1,000 substantial essays written by
more than 800 authorities from around the world, covering both the domestic
and international aspects of money, banking and finance.
As well as theory and doctrine, it also covers more empirical matters such
as institutional analysis and the workings of financial regulation, together
with the history of institutions, events and ideas.
It is out of the same stable, and has the same editors, as the New Palgrave
Dictionary of Economics published five years ago. The main geographical
focus is on North America and the US, with two thirds of its contributors
coming from the former region and a fifth from the latter. But efforts have
been made to cover the monetary and financial systems of about 30 other
countries, and Japan gets thorough treatment.
When it comes to entertainment, the new dictionary is too big and too
expensive for bath time reading. And some of its entries are daunting: the
explanation of intertemporal portfolio theory and asset pricing, several
pages long and laced with equations, is one of quite a few entries which are
not for the faint hearted.
But it is a real pleasure to browse through these volumes and come
unexpectedly across an elegant essay on money by James Tobin, a sour piece
on financial zoos by First Boston's Albert Wojnilower, or a full profile of
the Bank for International Settlements by Alexandre Lamfalussy.
Most entries are followed by a bibliography and there is a useful series of
cross references to send readers to relevant essays elsewhere in the text.
But will the dictionary achieve more than this? The editors' big idea is
that it will help to bring together the study of the subject 'money'  -
usually located in departments of economics in faculties of arts or social
sciences - with that of the subject 'finance', which is more usually to be
found in the universities' professional or business management school.
They recognise that the subjects have converged in recent years with, for
example, monetary theory being strongly influenced by an improved
understanding of the workings of efficient financial markets. But the
process has further to go. Only belatedly did the UK treasury come to
understand that the process of financial deregulation had played havoc with
the assumptions on which it had attempted to manage monetary policy during
the 1980s.
Perhaps the new dictionary will help. The editors hope at a minimum that it
will make financial economics more important in the training of general
economists. But it seems unlikely that such a densely structured work will
have a broader impact on the thinking of policy makers, academics and market
participants.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VIII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-4617</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CLACAAGKFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921201
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (15): Promoting the message
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILF ALTMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   EUROPEAN SALES PROMOTION
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GREAT CAMPAIGNS IN ACTION
by Alan Toop Kogan Page, Pounds 28, 208 pages
WHAT MAKES more and more blue chip companies spend a growing proportion of
their marketing budgets on sales promotion?
When Heinz runs a scheme offering customers prizes of 100 cars and Nescafe
in France offers free sample sachets of a new coffee to 10m households
(achieving an impressive 7. per cent acceptance rate) and even Sainsburys
takes part in BA's Air Miles bonanza, sales promotion has become serious
business.
Indeed, a good deal of the creative excitement which used to be associated
with advertising has switched to sales promotion, which makes it surprising
that literature and case material on the subject are still scarce.
Twenty-five years ago, as Alan Toop, one of the few serious commentators,
points out in this authoritative study: 'Most sales promotions were in
support of fast moving consumer goods: toiletries, soaps, detergents,
packaged goods, petrol and oil, beers, wines and spirits and tobacco . . .
Today the list includes cars, household appliances, furniture and
furnishings, clothing, airlines, railways, hotels, even banking and
insurance.'
More multinationals are running promotions in individual European markets.
Can it be long before pan-European promotional campaigns make their mark?
This is one of the issues Toop examines with insight. At the same time his
selection and dissection of campaigns in action shows how many leading
companies selling across national frontiers increasingly use sales promotion
as part of their marketing mix.
What determines the use of these techniques, often to complement rather than
replace media advertising? The short answer is sampling in the case of a new
brand, or to stimulate repeat purchasing or strengthen retail distribution
and display.
Sales promotion techniques are claimed in some cases to cost less than other
marketing tools, hence a large switch of expenditure towards promotion over
the years. Opportunities resulting from the growth of mass retailing in
Europe and pressures for short-term results are also contributing to the
demand for quick sales boosts.
The likely benefits of a well-planned promotion can be seen from one of the
many European case studies discussed by Toop. In Germany, Goodyear has a
chain of tyre and car service centres, but more motorists needed to be
induced to try the service. A 'Goodyear is looking for Winners' promotion
increased turnover in participating outlets by an average of some 25 per
cent during the promotion; the winning centre recruited 457 new clients; and
awareness of the service rose from 12.5 per cent to 30.5 per cent.
We are not told the cost of the promotion, but the results here, as for many
of the campaigns described, indicate why companies such as Unilever,
Coca-Cola, Range Rover and many others now use these techniques.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VIII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-4618</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CLACAAGJFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921201
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (13): Fun facts for all
fanatics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GUINNESS UK DATA BOOK
Guinness Publishing, Pounds 9.99,
192 pages
VITAL SIGNS - THE TRENDS THAT ARE SHAPING OUR FUTURE
Earthscan Publications, Pounds 9.95,
144 pages
BENJAMIN DISRAELI (or was it Mark Twain) is reputed to have observed: 'There
are three kinds of lies: lies, damned lies and statistics.' But these two
books attempt to dispel such cynicism.
The Guinness UK Data Book is a notebook-sized reference source which will
have instant appeal for trivia addicts, researchers and others fascinated by
the minutiae of life in Britain in the 1990s. It is packed with 'essential
facts and figures' which are intended to surprise as well as inform, and
covers everything from geography and religion to sport and social trends.
Fortunately it also comes with a reasonable index.
For example, it is possible to discover that almost 30 gallons of water a
day are used by each person in a household; that 63.4 per cent of the
population are Anglicans but only 4 per cent practise their faith; and that
the National Trust topped the list of charities with Pounds 55.73m in
voluntary income in 1990.
In contrast, Vital Signs is a reference book with a strong ecological
message. Produced by Lester Brown, president of the Washington-based
Worldwatch Institute, an independent research organisation, with researchers
Christopher Flavin and Hal Kane, the book focuses on issues such as: what is
happening to the world's fish catch? Third World debt, military expenditure
and CFC production.
Part one of the paperback describes 36 trends on double-paged spreads of
text, data and graphs which part two contains short essays on important
trends for which no historical or global data exists. Among its revelations:
world bicycle production now outpaces car production three to one; 80 per
cent of the world's 9,000 bird species are in decline, and world fertiliser
use has dropped for an unprecedented two years in a row.
It has a list of contents, but no index. Nevertheless it is well set out and
easy to read and should appeal to a wide audience.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-4619</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CLACAAGIFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921201
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (12): Mexico's long road to
recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MEXICO, THE REMAKING OF AN ECONOMY
by Nora Lustig
Brookings Institution, Dollars 28.9 5 hardback, Dollars 11.95 p/back,
186 pages
AT A TIME when optimism about economic prospects for the former Soviet Union
and east Europe have sunk to an all time low, it is consoling to read Nora
Lustig's account of the remaking of Mexico's economy.
One thing her book tells us is that rebuilding a broken economy,
particularly when world economic conditions are adverse, cannot be done
overnight.
After only three years, many observers appear to be losing faith in the
ability of the former eastern bloc to cope with its economic waste-land. But
as Lustig shows, it has taken Mexico ten years to emerge from the dark days
of 1982, when the government declared a moratorium on its debt, to the
present day when the Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development
is forecasting single-digit annual inflation and growth of 5 to 6 per cent
throughout the mid-1990s.
There are big differences between Mexico and the former eastern bloc
countries but there is one important parallel. Poor external conditions
stymied Mexico's economic progress in the 1980s, just as slow world growth
is now hindering the development of the bloc.
In a down-to-earth analysis of Mexico's economic rejuvenation, Lustig argues
that the main explanation for Mexico's slow economic recovery lies in the
adverse world economic conditions - scarce external credit, unfavourable
terms of trade and high real world interest rates - that prevailed since
1982. She argues that these factors prevented a 'bounce back' of the Mexican
economy after what should have been a two-year rather than an eight-year
adjustment period.
Falling oil prices and high world interest rates meant that the debt burden
worsened rather than eased as the decade wore on. This discouraged private
sector investment because of fears that the government would have to raise
taxes or resort to inflationary financing by printing money to keep up
payments. Whenever the government tried to deter capital flight by raising
domestic interest rates, private investment and growth were further
affected.
Second, lower oil prices, higher real interest rates and external credit
rationing hindered recovery by triggering a much larger relative cut in
public investment than in current government expenditures because the
Mexican government had to act quickly and found it easier to cut investment.
Last, with a heavy debt burden and poor external conditions, Mexico had to
devalue the peso in order to help generate a balance of payments surplus.
But this fueled inflation and further impeded recovery.
It took successive Mexican governments three attempts to defeat inflation,
restore business confidence, and encourage the return of domestic and
foreign capital. Once conditions were in place two crucial boosts to
confidence in 1990 - reprivatisation of the banks and the announcement that
the government would be seeking a free trade agreement with the US - gave
the spur to inward investment and economic growth.
Lustig devotes an entire chapter to the social costs of readjustment and
concludes that the economic strategy left a hard core of poverty that
economic growth alone may not be able to eliminate.
Also relevant to east European-watchers is the chapter dealing with public
sector reforms. 'The crisis and adjustment process provided an opportunity
to streamline the bureaucracy, improve the public sector's revenue
collection and expenditure mechanisms and redefine the nature and extent of
state participation in the economy,' writes Lustig.
Her conclusions on the success of the reforms are somewhat indecisive,
mainly because it is too early to judge the long-term results. However, she
believes that the reforms were successful in encouraging private investment,
and capital repatriation.
An account of the Mexican readjustment process is bound to throw up
interesting parallels with countries facing similar problems. Lustig's
thoughts on the Mexican experience are that while it teaches important
lessons its case is probably difficult to replicate: Mexico has an
acquiescent labour force and a uniquely cohesive and controlled state.
Nonetheless, the book's publication is timely. With the signing of a free
trade agreement with Canada and the US in August, there is evidence to
suggest that Mexico could be one of the fastest growing economies of the
1990s.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
