<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (11): High stakes in the ITV
poker game
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNDER THE HAMMER: THE ITV FRANCHISE BATTLE
by Andrew Davidson
Heinemann, Pounds 16.99, 318 pages
THE STORY of how the ITV franchises were put out to competitive tender and
the elaborate Pounds 1bn poker game that went on all over the UK for more
than a year is one of the most extraordinary in business history.
From January 1 both bidders and viewers will have to live with the
consequences. Several thousand television professionals will have lost their
jobs and about Pounds 300m a year will go to the Treasury instead of the
current Pounds 100m or so. Companies such as Thames, with a 25-year
programme making tradition, will head for the wilderness. In the depths of
an advertising recession some of the 'winners' could yet go to the wall for
bidding too high. There is also at least a question mark over how much
serious ITV programming can survive in prime time in what will inevitably be
a more remorselessly commercial industry.
Andrew Davidson has successfully captured the mood of the great game - the
surreptitious meetings in country house hotel, the bluff and double bluff,
the tension and the fear of putting a number in an envelope that will
determine whether a company lives or dies.
As he says, television is not only the most powerful communication tool yet
invented, it can also be 'one of the most exciting, frustrating, malicious,
greedy and cynical industries there is.'
The anecdotes bring out an additional dimension - the farce. They include
the story of how the executives from Granada, travelling round the Tyne-Tees
region in preparation for a hostile bid, ran straight into David Reay, the
Tyne- Tees chief executive, in the lobby of a Newcastle hotel.
Then there was the chaos of the Polygram, Palace Picture, Mentorn bid
against London Weekend. On the night before the bids had to go in someone in
their headquarters - the Groucho Club in London's Soho - tripped over a
computer lead and wiped out the eight page summary of their bid. They only
just managed to rewrite it in time for the printers.
Executives at Central, which bid only Pounds 2,000, nearly had a heart
attack when they picked up a story that the Rizzoli media group was planning
to bid against them with one of their own shareholders. In fact, they had
been discussing Centrale - the Italian word for the centre - in this case
London.
The funniest and most telling story of all comes from Christopher Bland,
chairman of LWT, who did not trip over any computer leads and saw off the
Groucho bid. Bland found himself sitting opposite to Sir Jeffrey Sterling,
the P&amp; O boss who had advised Margaret Thatcher on the broadcasting
legislation, in spite of knowing little about broadcasting.
'Oh Jeffrey,' said Bland. 'I've just been invited to head a commission to
look into the shipping industry.'
'But you don't know anything about shipping,' said Sir Jeffrey (now Lord)
Sterling. 'I think I know as much about shipping as you do about
broadcasting . . .' replied Christopher Bland, allowing time for his little
joke to sink in.
Apart from being an hilarious read the book provides useful insights into
some apparently inexplicable decisions, such as why TV-am thought it could
hold on to its franchise with a bid of only Pounds 14m - Pounds 20m less
than the winner - when it knew it faced two powerful rivals.
Andrew Davidson suggests, plausibly, that TV-am may have interpreted words
of praise from the Independent Television Commission for its Gulf War
coverage, its training and contribution to improving the broadcasting bill,
as a sign that it was safe, that the ITC would invoke 'exceptional
circumstances' to set aside higher cash bids. Thames Television, which bid
Pounds 32m, a figure that was unlikely to be the highest for the London
weekday franchise, clearly suffered from similar unfulfilled hopes.
Under The Hammer is an extraordinary tale of extraordinary events, but for
all the panache of its story-telling the book is light on analysis and
context and concentrates almost entirely on the big companies and the big
battles.
'Those looking for an answer to the perennial question, 'whither
broadcasting?' will search in vain,' the author explains. He does, however,
provide four and a half pages of explanation as an appendix. You also have
to look in the appendices for a significant interview with Mr George, now
Sir George, Russell, ITC chairman.
There the ITC chairman makes explicit what has been clear for some time:
that the ITC used the terms of the Broadcasting Act quite deliberately to
stop even more money flowing out of the system to the government. As a
result some rough justice was dispensed, both to existing ITV companies
which were deemed to have overbid and to outsiders which were excluded for
the same reason.
The consequences of the great ITV franchise battle are far from over. The
only hope now is that the government is capable of learning a lesson and
will approach the debate about the future of the BBC with a less dogmatic
frame of mind.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
