<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (10): Very dirty laundry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EVIL MONEY: ENCOUNTERS ALONG THE MONEY TRAIL
by Rachel Ehrenfeld
Harper Collins, Dollars 22, 298 pages
THERE IS an old saying among investigative journalists who are trying to
undercover a political or corporate intrigue: 'follow the money'. The saying
has become something of a cliche, but it remains as true as ever.
In the presently unfolding Iraqgate scandal - where officials of the US and
Britain appear to have broken their own export laws in an attempt to sweeten
Saddam Hussein with arms and money - the need to understand and to follow
the money trail is of primary importance.
Two of the banks caught up in the Iraqgate affair are discussed in Evil
Money, a new look at money laundering by Dr Rachel Ehrenfeld.
Dr Ehrenfeld is a woman of many talents - investigator, academic, journalist
and author. Her gifts were made apparent in an earlier book about
narco-terrorism and the Medellin cartel. This new book is a smorgasbord of
financial and political adventure. It includes new perspectives on the Bank
of Credit and Commerce International (BCCI) affair as well as a fascinating
inside look at the estimated one trillion US dollars of annual drug revenues
that are laundered through the international banking systems.
The book's great strength lies in its specificity. Dr Ehrenfeld takes us on
a voyage from the legacy of Meyer Lansky's offshore banking connections in
the Bahamas to the money laundering mechanisms utilised by the cocaine
traffickers of South America, detailing a demi-monde of front companies,
international bank wire transfers, bribe-taking politicians and crooked
accountants and lawyers. Its only weakness is that it does not draw this
vast subject together and make recommendations in a grand finale of a
concluding chapter. But this can be excused: Evil Money remains must reading
for anyone interested in the frightening interstices among drug traders,
terrorists, bankers and government officials.
</TEXT>
