<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (8): Cutting through the hot
air
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THIRD PARTY ACCESS IN EUROPEAN GAS INDUSTRIES
by Jonathan Stern
The Royal Institute of International Affairs, Pounds 12.50,
141 pages
AS THE EC single market approaches, most of the attention of the energy
industry has focused on Brussels' proposals to integrate the electricity
supply - by, for example, obliging member states to grant access to their
grid to suppliers from other states. Much less attention has been paid to
Brussels' parallel proposal to open up gas supplies on similar lines, even
though the effects could be just as far reaching.
This timely study from Chatham House is an attempt to shed light on these
issues. And what a tangle they are. As Stern points out, the European gas
industry is a tight-knit community of monopolies, many state-owned, whose
instinctive reaction to proposals of this sort is to say no. They have
deliberately exaggerated the problems and marshalled obscure technical
arguments in order to retard the pace of change. As a result the debate is
getting bogged down and is not sparking the amount of public interest it
needs.
There are times when Stern himself seems to have difficulty rising above the
complexities. He is frequently forced to comment that evidence is
'inconclusive', or to adopt over-wide generalisations in order to encompass
the subject, which is frustrating for the reader. Nonetheless one does
emerge from the study with a clearer sense of the issues and the direction
the debate is likely to take.
The Brussels plan is to open up third party access (TPA) to gas transmission
systems so that new suppliers can enter national markets. The aim is to
stimulate competition in a business where little or none has existed in the
past and, ultimately, benefit the consumer by increasing choice and driving
down prices.
The question is whether the merits of this plan are outweighed by the
potential threats to security of supply and to the stability that has
enabled the gas industry to make large investments up to now. Although Stern
dismisses some of the objections as scaremongering by the established
players, he does believe that the plan still has shortcomings.
His main concern is that while the Brussels TPA Directive lays out the
principles, it falls far short of being the sort of practical plan to get
things moving. He doubts that Continental EC members (the UK is different
because of the privatised gas industry and its special regulation set-up)
will be sufficiently motivated to put in place a pro-active regulatory
framework.
But Stern does see light ahead. He notes the key importance of the recent
growth of competition in Germany where, rather to people's surprise, certain
large players have forced their way into the market. By the middle of this
year, he also believes that other major players 'began to appreciate that
outright rejection was no longer a tenable position.'
But this will not necessarily open the way for implementation of a grand,
Brussels-driven plan. Instead he foresees 'a slow piecemeal, uneven
development of TPA on a country by country and perhaps even case by case
basis.' Change will be driven principally by the urge of the more aggressive
members of the gas industry to break into new markets. This will increase
the need for agreed international rules, at which point there will be a role
for the Brussels plan, though that will still be several years away.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page V
</PAGE>
