<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (7): What Clinton needs to
know
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DOMINICK COYLE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MEMOS TO THE PRESIDENT: A GUIDE THROUGH MACROECONOMICS FOR THE BUSY
POLICYMAKER
by Charles L. Schultze
The Brookings Institution, Dollars 24.95, 323 pages
THE US president-elect Bill Clinton is undoubtably a busy man right now as
he prepares to take over in January. One thing is for sure; he is not short
of advice, or free from special pleaders, or just from those wanting a job
on the Clinton bandwagon.
The campaign rhetoric and promises are almost history; what Clinton needs is
sound, experienced advice. Economists, officials, commentators and
hangers-on are offering solutions, but the man himself needs to understand
what they are telling him.
Enter Charles L. Schultze and his timely Memos to the President which
provides an essential, easy-to-read guide in language, to quote Herbert
Stein of the American Enterprise Institute, 'which even the President
(presumably it also goes for the President-elect) can understand.' Touche]
Schultze, now a senior fellow in the Economics Studies programme at the
Brookings Institution, was chairman of the Council of Economic Advisers
(CEA) during the administration of the last Democratic Party president,
Jimmy Carter, and director of the US Bureau of the Budget during the Johnson
presidency - not bad qualifications to advise an arriving president. The old
Washington fox has embarked on a personal fantasy, his own description:
'I imagined a new president (in the 1990s) promising the chairman of the
Council of Economic Advisers to devote an hour a week to learning about the
key economic relationships that a president ought to understand as a
background for making macroeconomic policy judgments. My fantasy then had
the president instructing the CEA to prepare a series of weekly memoes that
would accomplish that purpose.'
Schultze adds a qualification about his president, and a comment about
economic advisers of seemingly conflicting ideological persuasions. He
imagines that his hypothetical president and adviser come from near the
middle of the political spectrum, thus excluding the convinced supply-siders
of the early Reagan years or the left wing of the Democratic Party (that
should clear Clinton), and Schultze is not convinced that any one hundred
economists will have an equal number of macroeconomic prescriptions.
Noting his ten year association with the CEA, he observes that - nuances of
language and emphasis apart - the advice given presidents by both Republican
and Democratic CEAs was remarkably similar on about two-thirds to
three-quarters of the relevant issues. 'If one thinks of the views of
first-rank professional economists about issues of public policy as arrayed
across a spectrum of 180 degrees, from left to right, the middle third of
the spectrum would probably contain four-fifths of the economists.'
Having claimed for himself this broad middle ground, Schultze with admirable
clarity divides his 29 memos to the president into a three-part scheme. The
first four set the groundwork, with the nasty aside that many politicians
and journalists, and perhaps some professional economists, carry on the
public debate about macroeconomic policy in terms of what those policies
will or will not do to gross national product (GNP), but with only the
foggiest notion of what GNP is.
The next 15 notes deal with inflation and unemployment and explain how
economic forces produce short term changes of total demand and spending in
the economy; how these changes in demand, interacting with a more stable and
slowly changing supply, can generate inflation and unemployment; and how
economic policies can help keep total demand and supply more nearly matched
so as to avoid those consequences.
The nine memoes in the final part (memo 29 is a concise summary) are the
most interesting. They identify the principle forces that determine the pace
of long-term supply growth and consider the possibilities, costs and
limitations of government policies to promote it.
Schultze acknowledges that a host of microeconomic policy measures can
affect the growth of output supply: trade policy, environmental regulations,
minimum wages, agricultural policy. But he concentrates on three
macroeconomic contributors: national savings and investment in new plant,
equipment and infrastructure; the amount and quality of education embodied
in the labour force (here he finds the US educational system wanting); and
technological advance as it can be influenced by government support for
research and development.
The author writes that short-run changes in a country's economic fortunes
are dominated by changes in aggregate demand; policies to stabilise demand
can contribute to improving America's well-being by minimising periods of
high unemployment and inflation.
'In the long run, however, demand management is far less important than
policies to promote the growth of supply. Unlike stabilisation measures,
such policies typically produce gradual if initially imperceptible changes
in the nation's ability to produce goods and services. But these changes can
accumulate over the decades and generations and generate substantial
improvements in living standards. Continuing progress in the nation's living
standards depends heavily on growth of capital, improvement in the skills
and knowledge of workers, and scientific and technical advances.'
True, but what new president wants to hear such a long-term scenario? Yet
Schultze is correct when he says that getting economic policies at least
roughly right can make a big difference in the prosperity and growth of the
nation. In turn, understanding how the economy works is a prerequisite for
policymakers choosing the right policies. This book is an excellent starting
point.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page V
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-4625</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CLACAAGCFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921201
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (6): The rise and fall of
the Fairfax dynasty
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CORPORATE CANNIBALS: THE TAKING OF FAIRFAX
by Colleen Ryan and Glenn Burge
William Heinemann Australia,
ADollars 34.95, 457 pages
BEFORE Rupert Murdoch there was another, grander, Australian newspaper
dynasty. For more than 150 years, the Fairfax family wielded the sort of
power enjoyed for briefer periods by Northcliffe and Beaverbrook in Britain
and by William Randolph Hearst in the US.
It was staunchly conservative, retaining its trust in God, royalty and
empire long after many of its more egalitarian countrymen had begun to look
elsewhere for moral guidance. But it allowed its journalists a large measure
of intellectual freedom; and while its stewardship of the newspapers was
coloured by opposition to the Australian Labor Party, it acted, on the
whole, with dignity and honour.
By the 1980s, the family controlled two of Australia's leading broadsheets,
the Sydney Morning Herald and The Age in Melbourne, as well as the tabloid
Australian Financial Review; a chain of television and radio stations; and a
large number of provincial newspapers and magazines.
All dynasties end eventually, but rarely do they self-destruct in the
spectacular fashion achieved by the Fairfaxes. In 1987, after the global
stock markets' crash, 'Young' Warwick Fairfax, still in his 20s and a
Harvard graduate who thought he understood business, mounted a leveraged
buy-out of family shareholders. It was a fiasco.
Warwick would have inherited control of the company if he had been prepared
to wait for nature to take its course. Instead, he was taken to the cleaners
by other members of the family and his own advisers. He paid too much and
was unable to service the interest costs on bank debt of ADollars 1.25bn and
USDollars 450m of junk bonds.
By 1990, Fairfax was placed in receivership by its own directors and fell
into the hands of its bankers, principally ANZ and Citibank. Warwick
departed to live as a born-again Christian in Chicago.
The receivership lasted a year, during which bids were invited to buy the
group. There were three main contenders: a Melbourne-based consortium of
institutions called Australian Independent Newspapers (AIN); Independent
Newspapers, the Irish group owned by Tony O'Reilly, former rugby
international and chief executive of Heinz; and Tourang, a consortium
consisting originally of Conrad Black, Canadian proprietor of the UK Daily
Telegraph group, Kerry Packer, the Australian magazine and television owner,
and Hellman and Friedman, a US investment bank. (Murdoch would have liked to
bid but was ruled out on competition grounds: he controls about 70 per cent
of Australia's daily newspaper circulation).
Packer's involvement surprised no one; his family had been a down-market
competitor of the Fairfaxes for two generations. His father, Sir Frank, who
owned the Daily and Sunday Telegraphs in Sydney, sold them to Murdoch in the
1970s, leaving Kerry free to concentrate on television, and he was able to
take part in the Tourang bid so long as any holding in Fairfax stayed below
15 per cent. But no one seemed to believe Tourang's claim that Packer would
be a passive shareholder. Fairfax journalists, including Colleen Ryan,
campaigned actively against the consortium, as did a wider coalition of
journalists, politicians and academics.
Some of the opposition was heavy: Malcolm Fraser and Gough Whitlam, the
former prime ministers, patched up their differences to claim that an
Australian press controlled effectively by Murdoch and Tourang would
challenge the sovereignty of parliament.
Some was disingenuous: much of the comment in the Fairfax press was
presented as a debate on free speech, but was really aimed at forcing Packer
out of Tourang. Some was inept: an all-party letter to Bob Hawke, then prime
minister, urged him to block any bid which would increase media
concentration.
The book details the financial and political manoeuvrings which led to
Tourang buying Fairfax, giving Black a 15 per cent stake and management
control.
Tourang was always the favourite to win, mainly because it had an exclusive
agreement with the junk bond holders negotiated by Malcolm Turnbull, the
Sydney lawyer and merchant banker known best for beating the British
government in the Spycatcher case. But it was never easy, and the internal
tensions nearly tore the consortium apart before the deal was done.
The abrasive Turnbull was forced to resign his directorship after falling
out with Dan Colson, Black's Canadian lawyer; and Trevor Kennedy, formerly
Packer's right-hand man, was dropped as potential chief executive of Fairfax
after Colson and Brian Powers, Hellman's representative in Sydney, decided
he was a lightweight.
Most damaging of all, Packer was forced to withdraw after the Australian
Broadcasting Tribunal announced an inquiry into his relationships with
Colson, Powers and Turnbull. The tribunal, which had the power to block the
deal if it decided Packer was able to exercise control through associates,
acted after reading vitriolic diary notes written by Kennedy.
While this was going on, Labor faction leaders squabbled about how to
formulate regulations on foreign ownership which would keep out Packer and
Black while allowing in the supposedly more compliant O'Reilly. Right up to
the eve of the receiver's deadline for bids, Tourang was unaware what level
of foreign ownership would be allowed.
Ryan and Burge, both Sydney Morning Herald business writers, have produced a
comprehensive chronicle of events. But the book suffers from what might be
called the Insight curse - that style of journalism pioneered by the British
Sunday Times in which reams of extraneous detail are introduced for
verisimilitude. People are forever shuffling papers or coming in from
gardens rubbing dirt off their hands before taking calls.
The authors also dig deep into the cliche basket to bring us ashen-faced
stockbrokers, hard-nosed journalists, charming Irish leprechauns and sources
who remain adamant. The language is at best infelicitous, at worst,
ungrammatical. It is a typical journalists' book, long on detail and short
on judgment.
If you want to know which merchant banker sat down when and where with which
lawyer, Corporate Cannibals will tell you. But it has little to say about
whether the campaign against Black and Packer was justified; whether, as
often suggested, the Canberra government's media policy was formulated to
help Murdoch and disadvantage Fairfax; or whether the frequent changes of
the rules on foreign investment reflected the exigencies of a special case
or the special difficulties of doing business in Australia.
Conrad Black might have had something interesting to say about these points.
He once described Australian politicians as 'venal' and the bidding process
as 'a long, degrading, grotesque charade.' Not much honour and dignity
there.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
