<PROFILE>_AN-CLACAAGBFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921201
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (3): Leading questions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILF ALTMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A BRIEFING FOR LEADERS: COMMUNICATION AS THE ULTIMATE EXERCISE OF POWER
by Robert L Dilenschneider
Harper Business, Dollars 23.00
IS COMMUNICATION the ultimate exercise of power for leaders and would-be
leaders?
Churchill roared and Montgomery inspired. Here, communication skills were
prerequisites of great leadership. Yet admirable as it seems to elevate
mastery of communication as the key to modern leadership, there is surely
much more to it.
The author of this book at least has a good stab at trying to define these
wider attributes. He displays a voracious appetite for dissecting and
quoting from countless worthy management articles and books and case
studies, all meticulously indexed, and from personal encounters with
hundreds of business leaders, many of whom have obviously benefited from his
counselling.
All this distilled wisdom is well organised under four key headings:
leadership raw materials; the communication landscape; the communicator's
template; and leadership goals.
Modern leadership, he maintains, clearly rests on mastery of communication -
'What you say, where you appear, how you advance your message create a
portrait of you and determine how your leadership will be interpreted.'
The publisher's blurb leads one to expect at least a few rare insights into
the qualities of great leadership sorely needed in many contemporary fields,
but the promise is only half fulfilled. The author is at pains to stress
integrity and ethical standards, but the best we can find is a useful guide
to the development and deployment of communication skills to articulate an
organisation's vision, values and goals to both internal and external
audiences.
All this is practical and helpful stuff which ought to be known and
implemented by most business leaders and should be studied by those still in
the dark. Some of the advice will be ignored at one's peril even when other
major issues, such as surviving in recessionary times or lack of confidence,
predominate.
The more upbeat message is that 'leadership is a behaviour that can be
taught and learned' and that charisma is not a vital attribute - in fact it
is dismissed as bunk. Uncharismatic leaders can also be loved by being
'wired into every part of the company'. Many aspiring business leaders and
those still mystified by the powers of good communications will find this a
useful book.
</TEXT>
