<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (4): Polly Peck: the death
of a dream
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM HALE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ASIL NADIR AND THE RISE AND FALL OF POLLY PECK
by David Barchard
Victor Gollancz, Pounds 9.99,
288 pages
JUST OVER two years have passed since the collapse of Polly Peck, prior to
that of BCCI, the most spectacular London business failure in recent years.
The story is far from finished, since Asil Nadir's trial on charges of theft
and false accounting is not expected to begin until next March,
Nevertheless, pending further revelations, David Barchard has given us a
fascinating and thoroughly researched account of Asil Nadir's career, from
his early days as a tough and successful operator in the East End rag trade,
through to international business stardom and his eventual and sudden
downfall.
Barchard's book is based on extensive interviews with those involved, as
well as a long acquaintance with the Turkish political and business scene -
a central, but seldom explained part of the Polly Peck story. He makes sense
of a notoriously tangled web in a refreshingly crisp and engaging style.
In retrospect, the important questions about Polly Peck are not just why it
crashed, but why it seemed to be so successful for so long.
Part of the answer was that many of its reported profits were a mirage. Most
were derived from earnings from the fruit trade in Turkey and Northern
Cyprus, where inflation has run at around 50 per cent for most of the last
ten years, and the Turkish lira has steadily devalued in response. Polly
Peck's resultant foreign exchange losses were charged not to its published
pretax profits, but to reserves, and buried away in the notes to the balance
sheets. None of this was illegal, but resulted from what looks like a
serious weakness in the British accountancy rules.
It is also worth remembering that Asil Nadir identified and skilfully
exploited genuine opportunities, both political and economic. His family's
original emigration from Cyprus to London in 1959 was caused by politics
specifically, the impending British withdrawal from the island, and clear
signs that the Turkish minority would not be allowed to get ahead in
business in a Greek-dominated Cyprus.
Later, after 1974, the Turkish takeover of northern Cyprus gave Nadir his
first break outside the declining British textile industry, when he set up a
badly needed packaging plant to export citrus fruits now being grown by the
Turks.
A second and bigger opportunity arose in mainland Turkey in the 1980s, after
Turgut Ozal's government opened up a growing but hitherto highly protected
and inward-looking economy to the outside world. Asil Nadir seized the
chance, by moving into the fruit export business in Turkey with apparently
spectacular success, and then diversifying into consumer electronics and
tourism.
His expansion was part of that of Turkish capitalism, and resulted in an
alliance with its political sponsor, Turgut Ozal. To cement the alliance,
Nadir bought two newspapers and a magazine in Turkey which, almost alone in
the Turkish press, supported Ozal's cause. Nevertheless, in the final act,
Ozal declined to bail out Polly Peck.
The final collapse was partly caused by management shortcomings - in
particular, the fact that Nadir continued to run a giant corporation as
though it were still a small business - besides his disastrous bid to buy
out the company in September 1990.
However, his bankers must take their share of the blame. Only months before
the crash, the banks had been queueing up to lend Polly Peck hundreds of
millions, but then forced Nadir to fly round the world in search of a mere
Dollars 30m to try to rescue it from liquidation. Hone of them kept a close
enough watch on the company, until they were apparently scared off by an
investigation by the Serious Fraud Office - not into Polly Peck itself, but
a Nadir family company. Whatever Nadir's defects, the bankers' carelessness
also played a fatal part in the disaster.
In his last chapter, Barchard assesses Asil Nadir's undoubted talents, as
well as his failures, pointing out his compelling charm and negotiating
skills, as well as his intuitive grasp of innovative opportunities. His
description is not just that of a spectacular business career, but of a
fascinating personality. Whatever the outcome of Asil Nadir's trial, we are
unlikely to get a fairer, more thorough or lively portrait.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page III
</PAGE>
