<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (5): Maxwell: behind the
mask of a monster
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UNKNOWN MAXWELL
by Nicholas Davies
Sidgwick &amp; Jackson,
Pounds 14.99
NICHOLAS DAVIES served as foreign editor for the Mirror Group when foreign
coverage was not exactly a priority. The attitude of his last immediate
boss, Richard Stott, editor of the Daily Mirror who was sacked earlier this
month, was that most foreign news was of limited interest to 'tabloid'
Mirror readers.
What Davies lacked in serious employment (and he continues to deny that he
was ever involved in arms-dealing, as alleged in a book by US journalist
Seymour Hersh), he made up in experience as unofficial equerry to the late
Robert Maxwell, one-time newspaper magnate whose business empire collapsed
soon after his body was found floating off the Canaries just over a year
ago.
It is in his capacity as confidante at home and note-taker during Maxwell's
globe-trotting that Davies establishes his credentials not as a serious
biographer but as a competent diarist with a skilful eye for the telling
anecdote.
At home, Maxwell spent more time on his newspapers than on any other part of
his business, even though they were not the main generators of his wealth.
Maxwell showed neither editorial judgment nor inspiration as a publisher -
with the exception of his introduction of colour printing. But his
newspapers were a convenient playground in which to bully employees and
exercise other idiosyncracies.
The bullying has been well documented in an earlier Maxwell book written by
another editor of the Daily Mirror, Roy Greenslade. What Davies manages to
put together is a rather more terrifying picture of a megalomaniac who at
times tottered on the brink of insanity.
As Davies puts it in one of the few reflective passages to be found in this
entertaining book: 'There was an emotional restlessness about him, a
deep-rooted obsession, if not an unnatural urge to dominate and rule, and I
wondered whether his excitability and irrational behaviour amounted at times
to a madness.'
Stories of the difficulties in communication within the Maxwell empire are
legion. Particularly striking is Davies' tale of Maxwell regularly imitating
animal noises - a lion, a dog, and a duck to be precise - as he answered
calls. Maxwell's number was similar to that of London Zoo, so lines
sometimes got crossed.
Dialogue was no less civil in Japan where Maxwell once travelled to try and
get his MCC shares quoted on the Tokyo stock exchange. Davies describes an
evening when Maxwell, in full view of his hosts - executives from Nomura -
dispensed with chopsticks and attacked his dinner with his hands prior to
walking out of the restaurant. He had no time to waste on protocol even when
millions of shares were at stake.
In Japan, as in France, Argentina, Kenya, Poland, Bulgaria, and even Israel,
Maxwell promised much but delivered little. Investments were never realised
with success; instead Maxwell seems to have exploited the brief fix of being
treated as a visiting head of state, surrounded by a coterie of fawning
delegates.
It was in Moscow, (where Davies seems to have carried out an investigation
to complement his own notes), that a more lasting link was established.
Maxwell, while not a spy, was regarded as an 'agent of influence' by the KGB
and may well have played a part in funnelling Communist Party funds towards
the West.
Whether talking to communist bureaucrats or Latin American playboy
presidents, Maxwell always displayed a total lack of interest in the culture
and people he visited. He was happiest in no country in particular, but
drifting at sea, where he managed to go on bullying his employees from the
luxury of his boat, the Lady Ghislaine until he fell overboard in November
1991.
By then, as everyone now knows, the Maxwell empire was already not worth the
paper it was written on. Davies provides few fresh details about where the
money went and how. But he leaves us with an intriguing suggestion as to the
three people who might shed fresh light in the future. They are Dr Werner
Rechsteiner, Maxwell's Swiss lawyer; Ellis Freedman, his US lawyer; and
Vladimir Alexandrovich Kryuchkov, former chief of the KGB.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page III
</PAGE>
