compared with syndicated loans of Dollars 349m. In May, Paribas was lead
manager on Turkey's Ecu bond, a Dollars 185m-equivalent three-year exercise.
Commerzbank arranged a DM400m seven-year bond issue in July. Also in July,
the Treasury arranged a Dollars 250m Yankee bond issue.
When the samurai issues are included, Turkey is projected to be a net
borrower on the international capital markets in 1992, despite its original
target to be a net repayer. Debt repayments are estimated at Dollars 1.9bn
in the second half of this year. Public debt repayments are officially
projected to peak in 1995 at Dollars 4.6bn.
Due to these new borrowings and the adverse exchange rate movements which
are estimated to have added Dollars 2.3bn to the debt stock in the first
half of 1992, total debt is projected to reach between Dollars 53bn by the
year end. This is a net increase of more than Dollars 4bn over 1991.
Elsewhere, bankers described as rather optimistic suggestions from Romania
that it might follow the reopening of its domestic bond market after 45
years by tapping the Eurobond market as early as 1993. S&amp;P said the debt
rating for Hungary, the only eastern European country so far to have its
debt rated, is below investment grade at BB+.
THE European Bank for Reconstruction and Development has set an Ecu900m
borrowing programme for next year.
The bank has so far raised Ecu865m of this year's Ecu900m programme, at
economic funding levels. With an average maturity of seven years, the bank's
average cost of funds, after swapping the proceeds of its borrowings, was
better than 40 basis points below the London interbank offered rate.
Mr Rene Karsenti, the EBRD's treasurer, agreed it would be 'difficult' to
achieve the same cost of funds next year, but said the triple-A rated bank
'may benefit from the flight to quality' by bond investors.
The bank's policy is to borrow a minimum of 45 per cent of projected
requirements for cash disbursements over the next three years.
The money raised is invested in liquid assets, pending disbursement.
