<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 92 / Parliament and Politics: Borrie set to head Labour tax probe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR Gordon Borrie, until last June director-general of the Office of Fair
Trading, is set to head Labour's Commission into Social Justice - the
party's showpiece inquiry into the tax and benefits system.
The commission, proposed by Mr John Smith during his campaign for the party
leadership, is intended to examine key questions for Labour's future policy
proposals.
These range from the relative values of universal and means-tested benefits
and such issues as the merits or otherwise of progressive and redistributive
taxation. The exact terms of reference for the commission - widely
characterised as a new Beveridge report - and its personnel have yet to be
agreed.
However, Labour has confirmed that it will be independent of the party, will
be serviced by the non-affiliated left-leaning think tank, the Institute of
Public Policy Research, and its findings will outline options rather than
define positions.
About 12 other commission members are expected to be named, alongside Sir
Gordon, largely from the centre or centre-left of the British political
spectrum. Academics, Liberal Democrats and representatives of pressure
groups are all likely to be included.
The recruitment of Sir Gordon, 61, to chair the commission - still not
formally confirmed - will be seen as a coup for Labour.
Sir Gordon is a respected academic and QC with a long track record for
working on important social issues, who twice contested parliamentary seats
for Labour in the 1950s. At around the same time he published with Professor
Aubrey Diamond a seminal book on consumer issues, The Consumer, Society and
the Law, that formed the agenda for the consumer movement in later years.
Since then, Sir Gordon has served on bodies such as the Equal Opportunities
Commission while working for 16 years as OFT director-general, surviving, in
spite of his liberal credentials, the scrutiny of Mrs Thatcher's
premiership.
</TEXT>
