<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 92 / Parliament and Politics: Coal sale to await pit review
debate
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT would take no decision on the timing of British Coal
privatisation until both houses of parliament had been able to debate the
results of the pit closure review, Lord Wakeham, leader of the Lords, said
yesterday.
His assurance came as ministers were attacked by opposition peers for
seeking to press ahead with the bill paving the way for the privatisation of
British Coal and of British Rail while the review of the pit closure
programme was still under way.
The legislation allows the two organisations to appoint advisers to deal
with financial and legal issues in the run-up to privatisation.
The Lords voted not to delay the paving bill until early next year when the
white paper following the coal review is due to be published.
The decision to proceed marks the overcoming of a vital hurdle for BR
privatisation, already postponed for some months.
</TEXT>
