<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 92 / Parliament and Politics: Heseltine vows action against abuse
of market power
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHEN the government announced in 1987 that it intended to reform legislation
on restrictive trade practices and givethe authorities stronger powers to
tackle anti-competitive behaviour, consumer groups complained that the
government was addressing only half of the problem.
Yesterday's green paper, launched by trade and industry secretary Mr Michael
Heseltine, is designed to deal with the other half - abuse by individual
companies of their power in the marketplace to stifle competition.
The proposals are targeted at companies abusing their strength to try and
drive out competitors. They are also aimed at those who use their power to
take advantage of customers and suppliers.
Existing legislation dealing with abuse of market power in the Fair Trading
Act 1973 and the Competition Act 1980 is weak on deterrents.
Under European Community law anti-competitive practices are prohibited.
Companies which indulge in price-fixing or try to force competitors out of
the market fall foul of EC competition rules and can be fined up to 10 per
cent of their worldwide turnover.
However, under UK law a business accused of anti-competitive behaviour will
not be penalised unless and until it has been investigated by the
competition authorities and has subsequently broken undertakings not to
offend again. There are no powers to impose penalties for past conduct or to
provide damages for victims of abuse.
Because the UK law is seen as weak on deterrents many people argue that UK
competition authorities need stronger powers such as those wielded by the
European Commission.
The government is now seeking views on whether reform of the UK law along
these lines would be a good idea. But while adopting a regime based on the
EC system would appear to be the easiest solution, there are aspects of the
present regime the government is keen to preserve.
By adopting a case-by-case approach and not automatically assuming that
apparent abuse of monopoly power is against the public interest the UK
system is seen to be less rigid than the EC's.
The fundamental difference between the two systems comes in the definition
of market power. The UK takes a more broad approach. A business is deemed to
have a simple monopoly if it has 25 per cent of the market, irrespective of
whether it has real market power. The existence of a simple monopoly is
determined by a statistical test.
Under EC rules actual dominance is the issue. The commission takes the view
that a dominant position exists when a business has at least 40 per cent of
the market and its rivals have significantly smaller shares. Other factors
such as barriers to entry for new competitors and anti-competitive behaviour
are also relevant.
So instead of simply adopting an EC-based approach the government has put
forward three options for change.
The first is to strengthen the existing legislation. This would allow the
competition authorities to retain a case-by-case approach rather than
treating anti-competitive behaviour as automatically unlawful. But the
government would strengthen the investigation powers of the Office of Fair
Trading; give more scope to the director-general of fair trading to accept
binding undertakings from companies without an investigation by the
Monopolies and Mergers Commission; and make provision for businesses to be
sued for damages and possibly subject to civil penalties for continuing
abuse of market power after a complaint has been referred to the monopolies
commission.
The advantage of this is that it would retain the present flexibility. But
it would not address the fundamental problem of weak deterrents and it would
only offer limited redress to victims of anti-competitive behaviour.
The second option would be to introduce a general prohibition on abuse of
market power backed by tough investigatory powers for the Office of Fair
Trading and financial penalties. The monopolies provisions of the Fair
Trading Act and the anti-competitive practices measures in the Competition
Act would be repealed.
This would bring UK practice more closely into line with continental Europe
and would offer a more uniform system for companies operating in the UK and
in continental Europe. It would however cover more market situations than EC
rules do, and the government would continue to allow the competition
authorities to use divestment and price controls as remedies. The only real
drawback to this is that it would apply in a narrower range of market
situations than existing UK legislation because, for example, it would not
enable the competition authorities to look at possible market abuse by
duopolies or complex monopolies.
The third option is to repeal measures against anti-competitive practices
measures in the Competition Act and introduce a prohibition with the same
scope as the EC rules, but keep the monopoly powers under the Fair Trading
Act.
This is seen by the government as offering the best chance of an effective
deterrent while retaining the breadth and flexibility of the existing
legislation.
The disadvantage of this option is that operating two different systems in
parallel could increase uncertainty for business.
Under the second and third options companies could be fined up to 10 per
cent of their worldwide turnover for anti-competitive behaviour.
The government says, however, that in practice the competition authorities
would apply the Euro-style prohibition where a single company is accused of
abusing its strength in the market and the monopoly provisions of the Fair
Trading Act would be confined to detailed investigation of markets where
competition between a number of companies is not working effectively, and
where a complex monopoly operating against the public interest is suspected.
Abuse of Market Power - A Consultative Document on Possible Legislative
Options, DTI, Cmnd 2100. HMSO. Pounds 5.70.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
