<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 92 / Greatrex succeeds Lynk at UDM
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR ROY LYNK, the Nottinghamshire miners' leader who strongly backed
government privatisation plans for the coal industry, has been ousted as
president of the breakaway Union of Democratic Mineworkers.
He was convincingly defeated by Mr Neil Greatrex, the UDM's Nottinghamshire
area president, who is expected to take a more sceptical view of
privatisation.
Mr Greatrex won 2,326 votes to Mr Lynk's 1,586. The turnout was about 4,000
of the union's membership of about 15,000.
Mr Greatrex is a more traditional mining industry unionist than Mr Lynk and
called recently for a general strike against the pit closures.
He stresses, however, that whatever his personal views he will be subject to
union policy which supports an active role in the privatisation process.
Mr Greatrex also insists that his election will not lead to immediate
rapprochement with the National Union of Mineworkers.
The NUM claims to be winning members back from the UDM although the UDM
denies that.
Mr Lynk said after staging a sit-in protest at Silverhill Colliery near
Mansfield that he would step down from the presidency in protest at the
government's betrayal of his support. But he decided not to withdraw from
the election which Mr Greatrex had always been favourite to win.
Lawyers acting for the NUM are attempting to obtain government papers
concerning the selection of the 10 pits chosen for immediate closure under
British Coal's pit closure programme.
The move follows claims that selection of the pits resulted from dealing
between ministers and Tory backbenchers to avoid a government defeat over
the issue rather than assessment of their economic prospects.
</TEXT>
