<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 92 / Prior-year changes 'rare' in accounts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ONLY 5 per cent of British companies made adjustments in the past 12 months
to the figures shown in accounts of previous years in spite of the large
number of recent accounting changes, a survey by Company Reporting, the
Edinburgh-based monitoring service, showed yesterday.
The finding raises doubts about the ability of readers of accounts to draw
comparisons either with other companies or over time.
Prior-year adjustments are made by companies when their financial statements
are adjusted as a result of changes to their accounting policies. The
proportion doing so has remained roughly unchanged at 5 per cent for the
past three years. All but 14 per cent of the adjustments were made as a
result of changes in accounting policy.
Most adjustments were made for goodwill - the difference between the
purchase price of an acquisition and its net book value. Many of these
reflected new guidelines from the Urgent Issues Task Force of the Accounting
Standards Board.
Other common adjustments were made for revenue recognition, interest
capitalisation, post-retirement benefits, cost assessment and allocation and
corrections to prior-year figures.
Company Reporting. 68 Dundas St, Edinburgh EH3 6QZ. Pounds 315 a year.
</TEXT>
