<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 92 / Decision over risk weightings
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Bank of England yesterday disclosed that banks would not be forced to
increase the risk weightings of most forms of mortgage-backed securities.
Risk weighting is used in calculating the capital to be held against an
asset. The Bank said the weighting for mortgage-backed securities would
remain at 50 per cent rather than rising to 100 per cent.
Uncertainty over the level of risk weighting for the Pounds 8bn of
mortgage-backed securities in Britain was created by the EC solvency ratio
directive, which was published in 1990 and comes into force in January.
</TEXT>
